### PHP break and continue

`break` ends execution of the current loop. `continue` skips the rest of the current iteration and continues with the next.

### break

```php
<?php
for ($i = 0; $i < 10; $i++) {
    if ($i == 5) {
        break; // Stops at 5
    }
    echo "$i ";
}
// Output: 0 1 2 3 4
?>
```

### continue

```php
<?php
for ($i = 0; $i < 10; $i++) {
    if ($i % 2 == 0) {
        continue; // Skip even numbers
    }
    echo "$i ";
}
// Output: 1 3 5 7 9
?>
```

### Numeric Argument

Both `break` and `continue` accept an optional numeric argument for nested loops:

| Statement | Meaning |
|-----------|---------|
| `break;` | Break out of current loop |
| `break 2;` | Break out of 2 nested loops |
| `continue;` | Skip to next iteration |
| `continue 2;` | Skip to next iteration of outer loop |

> **Key Point:** `break` exits the loop entirely, while `continue` only skips the current iteration and continues with the next.
